{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-tag-js","path":"/blog/tag/ocean-plastic","result":{"data":{"wpgraphql":{"tag":{"id":"cG9zdF90YWc6MTI4","name":"ocean plastic","slug":"ocean-plastic","posts":{"nodes":[{"id":"cG9zdDozMjEw","title":"Plastic is Not the Villain — We Are","uri":"plastic-pollution-opinion-businesses-pact/","slug":"plastic-pollution-opinion-businesses-pact","date":"2018-11-30T10:34:42","content":"<p>The writer is Campaigns Manager at WWF-Singapore, Lotika Mehta The problem: our wasteful model of consumption.&nbsp; Countless times, I have been shocked and dismayed at supermarkets with the cashier&#8217;s reckless use of plastic, double bagging, or using a bag per item. Recent studies show that in Singapore, an average person uses 146 bags from supermarkets [&hellip;]</p>\n","author":{"name":"Lotika Mehta","slug":"lmehta","avatar":{"url":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/f845224f7c958c84c0ddec20e2e9875c?s=100&d=mm&r=g"}},"tags":{"nodes":[{"name":"marine pollution","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/marine-pollution/","slug":"marine-pollution"},{"name":"ocean plastic","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/ocean-plastic/","slug":"ocean-plastic"},{"name":"packaging","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/packaging/","slug":"packaging"},{"name":"PACT","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/pact/","slug":"pact"},{"name":"plastics in nature","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/plastics-in-nature/","slug":"plastics-in-nature"},{"name":"waste management","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/waste-management/","slug":"waste-management"}]},"categories":{"nodes":[{"name":"Ocean","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/category/ocean/","slug":"ocean"}]},"campaigns":{"nodes":[]},"featuredImage":{"sourceUrl":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Small_WW294915.jpg","altText":"","srcSet":null}},{"id":"cG9zdDozMjM0","title":"Why was There a Stranded Sperm Whale in Wakatobi, Indonesia?","uri":"beached-whale-plastic-pollution-wakatobi-indonesia/","slug":"beached-whale-plastic-pollution-wakatobi-indonesia","date":"2018-11-22T17:17:39","content":"<p>Last Sunday, a 9.5-metre sperm whale was found stranded off the coast in Kapota Island, Wakatobi — dead. Cause of death: unknown. But what we do know: a staggering 5.9 kg of plastic items found in its stomach. We talk to WWF-Indonesia&#8217;s&nbsp;Dewi Satriani&nbsp;to tell us more about this appalling incident. Below, global-exclusive information on the timeline [&hellip;]</p>\n","author":{"name":"Sharon Salim","slug":"ssalim","avatar":{"url":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/e36b8ae309f36dfc7c9fe446f89fd97d?s=100&d=mm&r=g"}},"tags":{"nodes":[{"name":"beach cleanup","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/beach-cleanup/","slug":"beach-cleanup"},{"name":"beached whale","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/beached-whale/","slug":"beached-whale"},{"name":"ocean plastic","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/ocean-plastic/","slug":"ocean-plastic"},{"name":"plastic pollution","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/plastic-pollution/","slug":"plastic-pollution"},{"name":"sperm whale","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/sperm-whale/","slug":"sperm-whale"},{"name":"stranded whale","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/stranded-whale/","slug":"stranded-whale"},{"name":"wakatobi indonesia","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/wakatobi-indonesia/","slug":"wakatobi-indonesia"},{"name":"wwf indonesia","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/tag/wwf-indonesia/","slug":"wwf-indonesia"}]},"categories":{"nodes":[{"name":"Ocean","link":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/category/ocean/","slug":"ocean"}]},"campaigns":{"nodes":[]},"featuredImage":{"sourceUrl":"https://dev-wwfsg.pantheonsite.io/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Screen-Shot-2018-11-22-at-4.21.48-PM.png","altText":"","srcSet":null}}]}}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"id":"cG9zd